/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most striking developments in the history of modern civilizations has been the conversion of tribal peoples to more expansively organized "world" religions. There is little scholarly consensus as to why these religions have endured and why conversion to them has been so widespread. These essays explore the phenomenon of Christian conversion from this world-building perspective. Combining rich case studies with original theoretical insights, this work challenges sociologists, anthropologists and historians of religion to reassess the varieties of religious experience and the convergent processes involved in religious change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConversionxHistory. 0aConverts. 0aMissionsxAnthropological aspects. 0aReligion and culture. 0aReligion and politics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abuddhism.  acentral australia.  achinese conversion.  achristian conversion.  achristian theology.  achristianity.  achurch community.  acolonialism.  acommitment.  acommunity.  aconversion.  afaith.  ainstitutional church.  ajesuit mission program.  ajesus movement.  amorality.  amuslim java.  anorthern mexico.  apapua new guinea.  aphilosophy.  apolitical economy.  arationality.  areligion.  areligious change.  areligious conversion.  areligious identity.  asociology.  asouthern african religious history.  aworld religions.1 aHefner, Robert W, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefner, Robert W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJordan, David K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKee, Howard Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato